\`\`\`

## Problem Analysis
1. **Per-insert lock:** DashMap locks shard on every insert
2. **High contention:** Many threads inserting to few agent types (~8 types)
3. **Scaling wall:** Beyond 8 cores, threads contend on same shards
4. **Unnecessary sync:** Could accumulate locally first then merge

## Proposed Solution: Rayon fold/reduce Pattern (RECOMMENDED)

**IMPORTANT:** Do NOT use thread_local! with Rayon. Rayon reuses threads from its
pool, so thread-locals persist between parallel operations and can cause data leakage.
The idiomatic Rayon pattern is fold/reduce:

\`\`\`rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use rayon::prelude::*;

fn discover_agents_optimized(paths: &[PathBuf]) -> HashMap<AgentType, Vec<PathBuf>> {
    paths.par_iter()
        .fold(
            // Identity: empty HashMap per worker thread
            HashMap::new,
            // Accumulator: add path to local HashMap
            |mut acc, path| {
                if let Some(agent_type) = detect_agent(path) {
                    acc.entry(agent_type)
                        .or_insert_with(Vec::new)
                        .push(path.clone());
                }
                acc
            }
        )
        .reduce(
            // Identity for reduction
            HashMap::new,
            // Reducer: merge two HashMaps
            |mut a, b| {
                for (agent, mut paths) in b {
                    a.entry(agent)
                        .or_insert_with(Vec::new)
                        .append(&mut paths);
                }
                a
            }
        )
}
\`\`\`

## Why fold/reduce Works
- **fold:** Each Rayon work-stealing task gets its own HashMap
- **reduce:** Merges HashMaps in O(log threads) steps
- **No locks:** All accumulation is local until reduce
- **Work-stealing friendly:** No shared state during parallel phase

